  "original_title": "\u0d89\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dd3\u0dba \u0db4\u0ddc\u0dc4\u0ddc\u0dbb \u2019\u2019\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0db7\u0dcf\u0d9c\u0dba\u2019\u2019 \u0dc3\u0db8\u0dad\u0dca \u0dc0\u0dd9\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Indian fertilizers have passed the \"test\".",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The National Fertilizer Secretariat informed the Agriculture Minister Mahinda Amaraweera that the urea fertilizer given from India is suitable for rice cultivation in Sri Lanka and other crops.",
        "The National Fertilizer Secretariat obtained a standard report in Sri Lanka regarding the urea fertilizer provided by the Government of India, and accordingly sent fertilizer samples to a laboratory in Sri Lanka and obtained a report regarding the percentage of biurate contained in them.",
        "The report has confirmed that the biurate percentage of the urea fertilizer is 0.9% and since the biurate percentage of the urea used in Sri Lanka was generally at the level of 1%, there is no problem in using Indian fertilizer for cultivation, the Fertilizer Secretariat has informed.",
        "Earlier, 03 international laboratory reports were obtained regarding this fertilizer, and those reports also stated that the percentage of biurate is 0.65%.",
        "According to the Ministry of Agriculture, Sri Lanka Commercial Fertilizer Company has arranged to distribute this fertilizer to agricultural service centers all over the island from today."
      ],
